    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>A Gastronomic Mystery</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>David Hoffman letter on January 2 article questions how people get seemingly instant reservations at restaurants in foreign cities</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor: Regarding ''Gastronauts, Shooting for the (Michelin) Stars'' (Jan. 2), I am utterly baffled by your article on people who will fly to a city at the drop of a hat and dine in a series of top restaurants. It seems impossible to me.</p>
        <p>I have no idea how these ''gastronauts'' get instant reservations for such places. When I have called to reserve at places like Robuchon's Paris restaurant, Charlie Trotter's in Chicago or The French Laundry in California with less than a month's notice, I have been met with a mix of politeness and gentle derision.</p>
        <p>David Hoffman  Sacramento, Calif.</p>
      </block>
